{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478808","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478808"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:16:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:16:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18844"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18844","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18844"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.27,0.1,0.58,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11577"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79677"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11577"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18844"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64980"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2210"},{"type":"tags","id":"9159"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27246"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79677","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79677"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent who is worried about a lump at his umbilicus that becomes more noticeable when he cries or strains. He was born at term with no complications and has no significant medical history. His immunisations are up to date and he takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a soft, non-tender umbilical protrusion measuring 1.5 cm in diameter that reduces completely with gentle pressure. The overlying skin appears normal with no discolouration or warmth.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Compression bandaging","Referral to paediatric surgeon","Ultrasound imaging","Observation with review in 6 months","Immediate surgical repair"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with a typical umbilical hernia, a condition that frequently causes parental concern despite its favourable natural course. The presentation is characteristic: a young child with a reducible umbilical protrusion that becomes more prominent with increased intra-abdominal pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObservation with review\u003C/strong\u003E represents optimal management in this scenario. The majority of umbilical hernias in children younger than 4 years spontaneously close as the abdominal wall muscles develop and strengthen. Regular monitoring ensures appropriate progression and allows early detection of any concerning changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate surgical repair\u003C/strong\u003E is not warranted in this case as there are no concerning features such as incarceration, significant size, or symptoms. Surgical intervention in this age group carries unnecessary anaesthetic and operative risks when natural resolution is likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompression bandaging\u003C/strong\u003E has no evidence base in the management of paediatric umbilical hernias. This practice may cause discomfort, skin problems, and provides no benefit in terms of hernia closure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral to paediatric surgeon\u003C/strong\u003E should be reserved for specific indications including symptomatic hernias, those enlarging after age 4, hernias exceeding 2 cm in diameter, or when complications develop. None of these criteria apply here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound imaging\u003C/strong\u003E adds no value in uncomplicated umbilical hernias where the diagnosis is clear on clinical examination. It would be indicated only if there was diagnostic uncertainty or suspected complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EParent education should focus on the benign nature of the condition and its likelihood of spontaneous resolution. While parents should be advised to seek medical attention if the hernia becomes painful, irreducible, or associated with vomiting, they can be reassured that such complications are rare in children.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Most umbilical hernias in children under 4 years of age resolve spontaneously without surgical intervention.","Surgery is indicated for umbilical hernias that are symptomatic, enlarging after age 4, or exceed 2 cm in diameter.","Complications such as incarceration occur in less than 1% of paediatric umbilical hernias."],"references":["Management of asymptomatic pediatric umbilical hernias: a systematic review Zens, Tiffany et al. Journal of Pediatric Surgery, Volume 52, Issue 11, 1723 - 1731"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64980"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18844"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64980","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64980"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T12:48:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T12:49:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11577"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79677"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"po